Over two weeks, there have been almost daily reports of clashes between Government forces and Renamo, one of the most violent clashes since the truce more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a known rebel movement supported first by the White authorities of Rhodesia and then by the South African Government of the apartheid era in an effort to destabilize the country ' s independent Government.
After the truce in 1992, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe that the country is unlikely to return to a full-scale conflict, but recent events have made foreign investors and locals nervous.
The stakes are high for a rapidly growing economy, as the discovery of huge shelf reserves of gas and coal deposits in the north-west can attract more than $50 billion in investment over the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale from Brazil, Eni from Italy, and Anadarko from the United States.
The ruling Frelimo party, the leading political force since 1975, and the Renamo party have accused each other of the tension that has arisen.
The Renamo Party claims that the Government was the source of the latest clashes by attacking its members in Sofala province, the traditional fence of Renamo, on 17 October.
