Here's the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With Eurocrisis, the Europe project is officially dead.
All over the European Union, parties opposed to the EU or for the euro to be abolished as a single currency are gaining power.
Even in Germany, the Euroskeptic Party “Alternative for Germany”, founded only this year, came out of nowhere and won almost five million votes in the September federal elections, thus effectively pushing “Free Democrats” (an analogy of our Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been an internal opposition to the federal European plan.
Nevertheless, the current economic crisis was a turning point.
The austerity measures introduced by Berlin and the European Central Bank and the shackles imposed on national economies through the preservation of a single currency led many to believe that the Europe project had gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments are working against excessive fiscal deficits — that was only true of Greece.
In fact, the euro system has blocked its members at exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters — what German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe is at a predetermined disadvantage in terms of production opportunities compared to Germany.
The only means of saving is to cut wages and public spending, which Berlin actively supports.
Behind the current problems of the budget and currency is the deeper problem of Europe’s productive capacity.
As a result of the Green Energy package introduced by Brussels — a cipher that means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the consumer’s expense — European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than in the United States.
It's a paralysing adverse price environment, as we've seen in Granjmouth.
No freeze on wages in the world will stop the devastating victory of US cheap slate gas over the European petrochemical industry.
As a result, there is an uprising, especially in France, once the most powerful supporter of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite viewed the EU as a way to control Germany and to place Paris at the same level as Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of gaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving France’s devastated economy in distress.
The result is a right-wing anti-EU party, Marín Le Pen, the National Front, just won the decisive additional elections by putting the ruling Socialist Party on third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 per cent of votes — a timely warning to British Labourers that it cannot be assumed that a split among the right will automatically affect the left.
What's Le Pen doing with her new-found popularity among the French white working class?
It wants to use the EU elections next year to create a block in the European Parliament against the EU and against a single currency.
If – and this is very likely – the anti-EU parties are supported in these elections, such a bloc will be able to dominate the European Parliament for the first time.
Here's my point: the growing mood against the EU and against the single currency in Europe will come together to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will again become a kind of vague “Europe (submissive) nations” that General de Gaulle liked.
Germany and several dependent economies can save the euro, but France and southern Europe will recover their own currencies.
