The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that was designed to carry genetic information for the production of anti-nickotin antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then produce a stable flow of antibodies.
Antibodies track any molecules of nicotine in the blood, neutralize them before they reach the brain, prevent the smoker from getting nicotine.
In the tests, the vaccinated mice, who were subsequently given nicotine, continued their normal activities.
And the mice that were not given the vaccine were "relaxed," and this is a sign that nicotine was reaching their brains, the researchers say,
