Indeed, demand in various parts of South-East Asia — where household debt is growing — is such that ValueMax, where it deals, became the third pawn shop registered on Singapore’s stock exchange this week.
A mortgage on jewellery is not just a quick way to get money (S$1,300 in the case of Ms. Amirthaling), but is almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Typically, pawn shops in Singapore charge an effective annual interest rate of 17%, slightly above the 15.4% offered at the United Overseas Bank branch, a local lender with a branch at the same mall.
However, pawn shops have the advantage that they do not require a credit test or proof of salary and can issue loans faster than banks.
Millions of people throughout the region are therefore forced into pawn shops because families feel pressure from higher costs of living and a rapid increase in household and consumer debt.
After five years of sustained growth following the global financial crisis and low-cost loans fuelled by free monetary policies in developed economies, low- and middle-income families turn to pawn shops to compensate for the decline in income as their economies slow down.
