On Thursday, data showed a continuing decline in exports and a decline in consumer demand.
“The point is that with rising prices, people in the middle and bottom [income scales] will look for ways to increase their income wherever they can,” says Song Seng Wong, economist CIMB, Malaysian Bank.
Recordedly high gold prices in the past two years have increased the rush with which people lay their personal belongings because they use the opportunity to get money for their family decorations.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the items laid in 200 city-state pawn shops are gold.
People say, "The gold price looks good, let's put a gold chain on Grandma and get it back next month."
In Thailand, the largest pawn shop operator, EasyMoney, has seen an increase in the number of clients using his offices in recent months, up to 20%.
