Scientists shed light on the way the dog’s tail moves are related to her mood.
Early studies have shown that happy dogs move their tails to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while alarmed dogs wave their tail mainly to the left.
But scientists now say that other members of the dog family can notice and respond to these subtle differences in tailings.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neurobiologist at Trent University, says: “It is well known that people in the left and right sides of the brain have different influences that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to look at it from other species.
He added that the right side of the brain controls the left side of the body, and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotion.
In order to learn more about how dogs react to the multiple tailings of other dogs, researchers observed animals watching movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of animals and analyzed their behavior.
We'll probably soon find out why their tails sometimes go one way and sometimes the other.
Professor Vallortigara said, "We showed dogs videos of dogs, either naturalistic versions or silhouette, to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the movement of the tail and direct the tail more to the left or to the right."
When animals saw that otherwise, the silent dog moved his tail to the right (from the point of view of the tail of the dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was leaning mainly to the left (again in terms of the tailing dog), their heartbeat increased and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said that he didn't think the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that the dogs learned from their experience which movements they should worry about and which they should not.
He observes: “If there are several encounters with other dogs and often one-way tails are linked to more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, the dog reacts on the basis of this experience.”
Researchers say that these results can give owners, veterinarians, and trainers a better understanding of the emotions of their animal.
An expert in dog behavior, John Bradshaw, an invited researcher at the University of Bristol veterinary school, said that this was not the first study to test whether the left and right side were relevant to the dogs.
Last year, a group of scientists at Lincoln University discovered that dogs turn their heads to the left if they look at an aggressive dog and to the right if they look at a happy dog.
And in another research paper at Victoria University in Canada, he reported: “The dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when the tail was pointing to the left rather than to the right rather than to become alarmed, the opposite of the Italian study.”
He said the difference could be because dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in films or robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
“Although there is sufficient evidence for various mammals that the two brain hemispheres are being used for different purposes, many details remain to be clarified, and dogs are no exception”, he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, we may soon understand why their tails sometimes go one way and sometimes the other.
