RBS suspends two currency traders
The Royal Bank of Scotland temporarily suspended two traders in its foreign exchange unit, according to two people familiar with the situation, which is further evidence that global scrutiny by the regulators of alleged currency manipulation is rapidly gaining momentum.
Some of the world’s largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank, and RBS, have confirmed that they are working with regulators to investigate the world’s largest financial market, with a daily turnover of $5.3 trillion.
These two traders will be the first RBS officers to be suspended during the unfolding investigation, which coincides with the LIBOR inter-bank manipulation scandal.
By refusing to comment on the suspension, the bank confirmed that it had received requests for information from the regulatory authorities this month.
“Our ongoing investigation into this issue is ongoing, and we are fully cooperating with FCA and our other regulators,” reported the bank two weeks ago.
Last month, informed individuals said that RBS had transmitted e-mail records and instant messages that had been received and sent by his former trader, the British regulatory authority, the Financial Performance Control Authority (FCA).
This trader, Richard Asher, left the RBS in 2010 and is known to have been granted leave for his current position as head of the European spot trade in JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, head of European spot tenders at Citi, took leave this week, while Matt Gardiner, a former senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended from work by Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders has been charged with any violations.
Mr. Asher's contact group for instant reports included bankers from Barclays and Citigroup, according to persons with knowledge.
The UBS bank reported this week that it had taken action against some of its employees after the Swiss regulator Finnma said that it was investigating alleged currency market manipulation in a number of Swiss banks.
At least six regulators around the world — the European Commission, Finma, Switzerland’s competition authority, Weko, FCA, the U.S. Department of Justice, and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority — are considering allegations that bankers conspired to influence the currency market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also started internal checks or received requests for information from regulators, who are familiar with the situation.
Banks have been looking at instant messages and e-mails over several years in search of offences.
The verification news has sparked the activities of traders, which in recent years has been one of the largest sources of revenue from investment bank trading units, which this year, however, has encountered difficulties in view of the fact that low currency volatility has reduced opportunities for buyers.
Some bankers have tried to reduce the seriousness of the situation by saying that a large and highly liquid currency market is almost impossible to manipulate, but senior traders say that this is not always true.
According to the senior trader, despite the huge volume of daily foreign exchange tenders, the fragmentation of liquidity between different trading platforms and the wider use of domestic platforms by banks means that “you can begin to influence the market at a very low price”.
This news came on the same day that Credit Suisse announced that it had fired one of the traders of its stock trade division in London this week after it had caused nearly $6 million in losses at the end of last year.
