Mohammed Morsi is sworn in, but the day of its celebration is unlikely to mark the end of the political struggle in Egypt.
ISLAMIST Mohammed Morsi promised a “new Egypt” when he took the oath to become the first freely elected President of the country, replacing Hosni Mubarak, who was overthrown 16 months ago.
At his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Mursi also became the first freely elected Islamist president of the Arab world and fifth head of State in Egypt after the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He took an oath before 18 judges wearing black robes in a courthouse on the shore of the Nile, built in the style of an ancient Egyptian temple.
“We seek a better future, a new Egypt and a second republic,” said Morsi during a solemn ceremony broadcast live on State television.
“Today, the Egyptian people laid the foundations for a new life — absolute freedom, true democracy and stability,” said Morsi, a 60-year-old engineer with an American Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that, for most of its 84 years, was a banned organization that was targeted by successive governments.
The building was guarded by hundreds of soldiers and policemen when Morsi arrived with a small convoy shortly after 11 a.m. local time.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered outside the court building to welcome the new President, and unlike the presidential pump of Mubarak, the movement was stopped only for a short time to allow his convoy to pass on the normally lively road linking the centre of the city to the southern suburbs.
Although Morsi was ridiculed as a non-charismatic spare wheel of the Brothers, his personal prestige has increased dramatically since his victory and his Friday performance, in which he tried to present himself as a candidate not only for Islamists, but also for all those who want to complete the 2011 rebellion against authoritarian Mubarak.
“Today, Egypt is a civil, national, constitutional and modern state,” said Morsi, wearing a blue business suit with a red tie, to judges in a wooden room where he took the oath.
