Travel on dirt, rivers and jungles to provide free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwellet provides free medical care in rural Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend receiving hundreds of patients.
There are not many doctors in this West African country -- just one per 5,000 people.
Vote here or through your mobile device.
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 heroes of CNN 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 major heroes to become the hero of the year CNN.
This man will get $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle saw his father come back to life and become unconscious again, wandering around hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jameth Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only a broken arm, but the infection had spread to the brain and caused a hematoma that reminded him of itself for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” Georges Bwella said.
If we had the money, we'd have taken him out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwelle accompanied his father for years in overcrowded clinics and hospitals, receiving any treatment they could receive.
“It's not easy,” said Bwella.
- You can leave the house at 5:00 a.m., run to the hospital to be the first, but you're not the first.
There's a lot of patients.
Some people might die because they have to wait.
The situation has not changed much since Father Bwelle died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, Cameroon has only one physician per 5,000 people.
By comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if Cameroonians could go to a doctor, many of them would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three quarters of health spending are private.
“The only problem is poverty,” said Bwella.
“And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy their lives.”
When he saw the suffering of his father and many of his compatriots, Bwelle was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team conducted 700 free operations.
He himself became a doctor and works as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
He also established a non-profit organization, ASCOVIME, which organizes weekend visits to rural areas to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have provided assistance to nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 others are loaded into vans, tied to roofs with medical supplies and travelling across the border to visit villages in need.
It's not always their luck.
They've had to push cars through rivers and dirt on many occasions.
But when they come, they're greeted as real heroes: it's a holiday with songs and dances and the best rooms the locals can offer.
Free medical care in these villages is indeed an occasion for celebration, and Bwelle is more than happy to join the fun with his broad smile and unlimited energy.
The next morning, the team begins to receive hundreds of patients.
“We receive 500 people on every trip,” Bwella said.
They come from all over the county within a radius of 60 kilometres from the village, and they walk.
Each of these clinics provides a variety of medical services on a day-to-day basis.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, sunglasses, or free birth certificates — documents needed for school, which many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evenings, the team conducts simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually conducted in the school building, municipality or home; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the post-op zone to vacate space for the next person.
Using the generator to illuminate the operating and sanitary treatment of the equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers operate until early Sunday morning.
It's a slow pace, but the team's commitment usually helps support village musicians.
“They've been hitting drums all night to keep us awake and keep working,” said Bwella.
On Sunday, the crew members go back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group, composed of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students, carried out 700 free surgeries over the past year, and they know that their assistance can be of great importance to those they help.
One person explained that the free hernia treatment he received would allow him to work again.
“It will change the future for me and my family,” the man said.
In addition to these clinical treatments on weekends and work at the hospital, surgeon Bwelle also works at night in private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
It was this second job, he said, that provided 60 per cent of the funding for his non-profit organization; the rest was covered by private donations.
"I don't even know when he's sleeping," said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia, volunteering for the Bwell Group.
He's either in the hospital or he's trying to make money for the organization so he can continue these campaigns.
For future doctors and nurses, such as O'Malley, coming from the United States and Europe to join Bwell in his tasks, it is an opportunity for practice that they would never have received at home.
“We were able to assist in operations where we helped remove blood stains or hold instruments for Dr. Bwelle”, O'Malley said.
As a second-year student, you'd never get that opportunity in America.
Visitors usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon, often with donated medicines.
But when they arrive in Yaoundé, their food, transportation and training are paid by Bwella.
"He's a hero, no doubt," said O'Malley.
He is giving his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is infinite.
For Bwella, almost constant workload is not a difficult test.
Helping others to live a happy life, fulfilling their father’s promise, is something that brings him great joy.
“I am so happy when I do this job,” said Bwella.
- And I'm thinking about my dad.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I'm doing this to make people laugh to reduce their pain.
Go to ASCOVIME and see how you can help.
