Australian woman appeals against prison terms in Thailand
A 21-year-old woman from Sydney, sentenced to 15 days in prison on Phuket Island for falsely claiming that she had been attacked by a taxi driver, appealed the sentence and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty on 15 June by the Phuket Provincial Court of bringing a false action following a report by the Thai police that a local taxi driver attacked on the night of Sunday, 10 June, while two other men held her.
However, surveillance footage later revealed that she had returned safely to her hotel after breaking up a relationship with her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police interrogated Bamford for two days before she confessed to fabricating the story.
She was held in local police cells until trial.
Bamford was sentenced to a 15-day prison sentence at the general security detention centre on the outskirts of Phuketta, not at the adult women ' s prison.
She is the daughter of a former Australian League player, Peter Tanks, who applied to the Department of Foreign Affairs in Canberra for help for his daughter.
Tanks told Sydney’s Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was “extremely concerned” about her daughter’s well-being and waited for her to return to Australia.
“It was obviously an alarming time, but we hope that she will return safely to her home as soon as possible,” said Tanks.
Bamford appealed her sentence and was released on bail of 50,000 baht.
According to reports in Australia, she is currently spending her vacation in the Krabi resort in southern Thailand.
Legal sources in Thailand reported that Bamford was currently represented by a local lawyer in Phuket, but warned that the appeal could result in the court extending her sentence to two years and forcing her to serve her sentence in an adult prison.
However, following the recent assassination of Australian travel agent Michelle Smith in Phuket, Thailand may also seek to restore its damaged tourist image, leading to acquittal.
